#compdef rag
# =============================================================================
# rag — Bae Hyun-sol's "ragit" — a "git-like RAG (Retrieval-
#       Augmented Generation) pipeline" — a Rust CLI for
#       building, managing, and querying RAG knowledge bases
#       used by Large Language Model (LLM) applications.
#       Mirrors git's command structure (init / add / clone /
#       push / pull / status / etc.) but applied to RAG
#       indexes of source documents.  Indexes are stored in
#       `.ragit/` directories (analogous to `.git/`), making
#       knowledge bases version-controllable and shareable.
#       Distinguishing from LangChain (Python framework),
#       LlamaIndex (Python), and other RAG tools by:
#         - GIT-LIKE WORKFLOW — every operation mirrors git's
#           UX:
#             rag init                              # create .ragit/
#             rag add doc1.md doc2.md               # stage docs
#             rag build                             # process + embed
#             rag push https://my-rag-server.com    # push to remote
#             rag pull https://my-rag-server.com    # pull updates
#             rag clone https://my-rag-server.com   # clone full RAG
#             rag query "What is X?"                # query LLM
#             rag status                            # show staged
#             rag config --set api.model=gpt-4
#             rag config --get-all
#         - 35+ SUBCOMMANDS via custom ragit-cli parser:
#             * init / clone / status / merge       (git-like vault ops)
#             * add / remove (rm) / cat-file        (doc staging)
#             * build / pull / push                 (process + sync)
#             * query / chat / agent                (LLM interaction)
#             * config (--get/--set/--get-all)      (settings)
#             * model / ls-models                   (LLM selection)
#             * meta (--get/--set/--add/--remove)   (metadata)
#             * archive-create / archive-extract    (vault export/import)
#             * gc                                  (garbage collect old chunks)
#             * audit                               (security audit)
#             * check                               (integrity verify)
#             * extract-keywords / summary          (NLP utilities)
#             * ii-build / ii-reset / ii-status     (inverted index)
#             * ls-chunks / ls-files / ls-images    (vault inspection)
#             * ls-queries / ls-terms               (query/term tracking)
#             * migrate                             (vault version migration)
#             * help / --help / version             (meta)
#         - MULTI-MODAL SUPPORT — text + images + PDFs (mupdf
#           feature) + SVGs (resvg feature); chunks include
#           image embeddings via vision models
#         - MULTI-PROVIDER LLM SUPPORT — OpenAI / Anthropic /
#           local Ollama / vLLM / LM Studio / cohere / together /
#           Azure / AWS Bedrock all configurable via `rag config
#           --set api.provider=X`
#         - PDL (Prompt Description Language) — ragit-pdl
#           crate defines a custom DSL for declaring LLM
#           prompts with schema validation; runtime renders
#           via tera template engine
#         - KOREAN-LANGUAGE TOKENIZATION — ragit-korean crate
#           provides Hangul-aware tokenization for Korean
#           document RAG (author is Korean)
#         - INVERTED INDEX (ii) — ragit-ignore + ragit-fs
#           build a search index over chunks; supports
#           keyword + semantic + hybrid retrieval
#         - SHA3-256 CONTENT ADDRESSING — chunks identified by
#           SHA3 hash (sha3 crate); enables content-addressable
#           storage similar to git's blob hashing
#         - DIFF-BASED PULL — ragit-fs's diff feature computes
#           delta between local + remote vaults; pull transfers
#           only changed chunks (efficient sync over network)
#         - FLATE2 COMPRESSION — chunks compressed via flate2
#           crate for storage efficiency
#         - REQWEST MULTIPART HTTP — API calls (LLM providers,
#           remote vault servers) via reqwest with multipart
#           support for image uploads
#         - TOKIO ASYNC RUNTIME — all I/O async via tokio
#         - RAG-CLI / RAG-API / RAG-FS / RAG-IGNORE / RAG-PDL /
#           RAG-KOREAN CRATES — modular workspace with 6
#           internal crates for clean separation of concerns
#       Used by: LLM application teams building production
#       RAG pipelines over corporate knowledge bases, AI
#       researchers needing reproducible RAG benchmarks
#       (with git-like reproducibility), Korean-language NLP
#       teams (special tokenization), and as a reference
#       implementation of tera templates + reqwest + tokio +
#       sha3 + flate2 + image + custom ragit-cli composition
#       in Rust LLM tooling.
#
# Author:  Bae Hyun-sol (baehyunsol on GitHub) — Korean Rust
#          developer focused on LLM tooling.  ragit released
#          ~2024; current version 0.4.6; active development
#          through 2026.  License: MIT.
# Source:  https://github.com/baehyunsol/ragit
#          https://github.com/baehyunsol/ragit/blob/master/src/main.rs
#          https://github.com/baehyunsol/ragit/blob/master/Cargo.toml
#          https://github.com/baehyunsol/ragit/tree/master/crates
# CLI:     src/main.rs — uses custom ragit-cli ArgParser (not
#          clap / structopt).  Headline library: **tera**
#          (the new variant being documented here, opening
#          Axis 21 — Templating Engines).
# Library: tera (https://github.com/Keats/tera —
#          "A template engine for Rust based on Jinja2/Django"
#           — Vincent Prouillet (Keats on GitHub).
#           Distinct from all previously-documented Rust
#           libraries by being:
#              1. JINJA2 / DJANGO-INSPIRED SYNTAX — tera uses
#                 the Jinja2 template syntax (also Django,
#                 Twig, Nunjucks, Liquid family):
#                   <h1>Hello {{ name }}!</h1>
#                   {% for item in items %}
#                     <li>{{ item.name }}: {{ item.price | currency }}</li>
#                   {% endfor %}
#                   {% if user.is_admin %}
#                     <a href="/admin">Admin</a>
#                   {% endif %}
#                   {% include "partial.html" %}
#                   {% extends "base.html" %}
#                   {% block content %}{% endblock %}
#                 Distinct from handlebars (Mustache family),
#                 askama (compile-time Rust template),
#                 minijinja (Armin Ronacher's runtime Jinja2),
#                 and text/template (Go stdlib).
#              2. RUNTIME-COMPILED TEMPLATES — tera compiles
#                 templates at runtime (not at Rust compile
#                 time).  Distinct from askama (compile-time
#                 typed templates with proc-macros) and
#                 minijinja (also runtime).  Allows dynamic
#                 template loading + editing without
#                 recompilation.
#              3. ZOLA-BACKED — tera is the template engine of
#                 Zola (https://www.getzola.org), the most
#                 popular Rust static site generator.  Zola
#                 ships tera + Sass + CSS + Syntect into a
#                 single self-contained binary.  Tera is
#                 battle-tested through thousands of Zola sites.
#              4. INHERITANCE + INCLUDE — {% extends %} and
#                 {% include %} for template composition;
#                 {% block %} / {% endblock %} for inheritance
#                 override points.
#              5. FILTERS — `{{ value | filter_name }}` syntax
#                 for value transformations.  Built-in filters
#                 include length, lower, upper, title, trim,
#                 truncate, escape, escape_xml, capitalize,
#                 reverse, sort, unique, group_by, filter,
#                 map, concat, urlencode, json_encode,
#                 date, get_random, abs, round, plus,
#                 minus, times, divided_by, modulo, ... (~60
#                 built-ins).  Custom filters via
#                 tera.register_filter("name", fn).
#              6. TESTS — `{% if value is even %}` /
#                 `{% if items is empty %}` syntax for
#                 typed predicates.  Built-in tests:
#                 odd, even, divisibleby, defined, undefined,
#                 string, number, ... ; custom tests via
#                 tera.register_tester("name", fn).
#              7. CUSTOM FUNCTIONS — Rust functions registered
#                 as `{{ function_name(arg=val) }}` calls
#                 inside templates: tera.register_function(
#                 "now", |_args| Ok(chrono::Utc::now().into()));
#              8. CONTEXT API — `tera::Context` struct for
#                 passing variables; insert<T: Serialize>
#                 method serializes Rust structs into the
#                 template context via serde.
#              9. ERROR REPORTING — line + column + template-
#                 name for template syntax errors; detailed
#                 error chains for runtime errors.
#             10. VINCENT-PROUILLET / Keats ECOSYSTEM
#                 PROVENANCE — Vincent Prouillet (Keats on
#                 GitHub) maintains a full Rust static-site /
#                 templating stack:
#                   * tera           — Jinja2 templates       (THIS)
#                   * zola           — static site generator
#                   * jsonwebtoken   — JWT library
#                   * gutenberg      — early SSG name (renamed
#                                       to Zola in 2018)
#                   * orogene        — npm replacement
#                                       (experimental)
#                   * config-rs      — config file loader
#                                       (Axis 13 entry)
#                 Keats's libraries form the Rust "Sergio
#                 Benitez of static sites" — opinionated,
#                 high-quality, single-author maintenance.)
# License: MIT (tera); MIT (ragit)
# Status:  tera — 4,214+ stars on Keats/tera, ~80M crates.io
#          downloads (TOP-50 Rust crate by downloads);
#          foundational templating library used by:
#            * Zola (Rust static site generator — Keats's own
#              project)
#            * mdbook (some plugins)
#            * cargo-generate (project scaffolding templates)
#            * Rocket (web framework templates)
#            * Actix-web (templates)
#            * Sublime Text plugin testing tools
#            * various Rust web frameworks
#            * ragit (THIS — LLM prompt templating via PDL)
#            * 2000+ Rust applications
#          ragit — 257+ stars on baehyunsol/ragit, used by
#          LLM application teams building production RAG
#          pipelines.
#
